', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Marta', 'last_name': 'Peleteiro Ramallo', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Entrepreneur and Creative Consultant'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Carolina', 'last_name': 'A.', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Innovation Consulting | EU Funding | EIC Accelerator Expert'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'María', 'last_name': 'Tomé Moreno', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Communications & Influencer Marketing Specialist'}]}, {'title': 'NO ME PONGAS LOS CUERNOS Inéditos 2012', 'date': {'start': {'month': 7, 'day': None, 'year': 2012}, 'end': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2012}}, 'description': 'NO ME PONGAS LOS CUERNOS is an exhibition at La Casa Encendida in Madrid that invites us to peer through a Nordic window, using a Viking legend as its centrepiece in order to explore the notion of sound and aesthetics within an experimental field in a context taken to the ironic plane. The title of the show is a play on words: the literal meaning is “don’t put horns on me”, but the use of the Spanish set phrase ponerse los cuernos (to be unfaithful, to cuckold) means that it could also be construed as “don’t cheat on me”. Thus, wrapped in a recurrent witticism from the Latin and Hispano-American world, Nordic culture progresses beyond the ornately fascinating, allowing us to sense and perceive another step towards an alien context rendered unnatural by language and the iconic game in culture.      

Artists: CAROLINE MÅRTENSSON, METTE BORUP KRISTENSEN, INGEN FRYGT, LOUISE BERTELSEN, NIELS PEERAER, ANNI HOLM, PJUSK, MARTINI PROJECTS, ECTOPLASM GIRLS, TOVE KJELLMARK, MAIKEN BENT, SOGAR

Gothenburg.', 'date': {'start': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': None}, 'end': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': None}}, 'description': 'SURPLUS WORK: THE NON/DISPLAY OF SWEDISH LABOR MOVEMENT ART

Artwork from the archive of Folket Hus and new work by Leonor Serrano Rivas (Spain)

The exhibition deals with radical changes in the use value of artworks produced for the Swedish Labor Movement that have been concealed from public view—behind curtains or unceremoniously stacked in basements—as their institutions are redefined and restructured.  Guided by the notion that location and mode of reception has an affect on a work of art, this exhibition presents a series of gestures and traces reflecting these artworks’ current situation, including a new site-specific installation by Spanish contemporary artist and architect Leonor Serrano Rivas exploring ways to seek actualization of potential values for these artworks.

Curated by Cecilia Eriksen Wijk (Sweden), Marta Peleteiro Ramallo (Spain) Michaela Nilsson (Sweden), Patrik Haggren (Sweden)
